      "output": "The sky looks blue because of **Rayleigh scattering**, a physical process that occurs when sunlight passes through Earth\u2019s atmosphere.\n\n### How it works\n\n1. **Sunlight is a mixture of all colors** \u2013 the visible spectrum runs from violet (short wavelength) to red (long wavelength). When combined, these colors appear white.\n\n2. **Molecules and tiny particles in the air act like tiny prisms**. When light hits them, it is scattered in all directions.\n\n3. **Short\u2011wavelength light (blue and violet) scatters much more efficiently** than long\u2011wavelength light. The scattering intensity varies roughly as\u202f1/\u03bb\u2074, so blue (\u2248450\u202fnm) is scattered about ten times more than red (\u2248650\u202fnm).\n\n4. **Our eyes are more sensitive to blue than violet**, and some of the violet is absorbed by the upper atmosphere, so the scattered light that reaches us looks predominantly blue.\n\n5. **The scattered blue light comes from every part of the sky**, so wherever you look, a portion of that blue\u2011shifted sunlight is being sent into your eye.\n\n### Why the sky changes color at sunrise and sunset\n\nWhen the Sun is low on the horizon, its light must travel through a much thicker layer of atmosphere. The longer path means even more blue and violet light is scattered out of the direct line of sight, leaving a higher proportion of red and orange wavelengths to reach you. That\u2019s why the sky near sunrise or sunset appears reddish.\n\n### Other factors\n\n- **Clouds and haze** contain larger water droplets or particles. These scatter all wavelengths more equally (Mie scattering), giving clouds a white or gray appearance rather than blue.\n- **Air pollution** can add particles that also scatter light more uniformly, sometimes giving the sky a milky or brownish tint.\n\nIn short, the blue color of a clear daytime sky is the result of sunlight being preferentially scattered by tiny atmospheric molecules, with our eyes perceiving that scattered light as blue.",
